        "text": "Is there any limitation as for the number of attached USB input devices in DCS?\n\nI plan to add two more USB controllers so that I will have 6 total.\n\n(Joy, Throttle, Pedals, Axis module, Trim module and Switches module)\n\nTHX\n\nWell, to tell the truth, I did not counted Keyboard, Mouse and TIR.\n\nSo the planed number is 9 total :-)\n\nWell, they are USB devices that have to be recognized by DCS just like your joystick, throttle and so on ;)\n\nI don't know if there's a limit for input devices in DCS (or Windows!). :dunno:\n\nIs there any limitation as for the number of attached USB input devices in DCS?\n\nI plan to add two more USB controllers so that I will have 6 total.\n\n(Joy, Throttle, Pedals, Axis module, Trim module and Switches module)\n\nTHX\n\nShouldn't be a problem. I'm pretty sure DCS will recognize as many USB input devices as your operating system can detect, and it's a lot.\n\nSo just go ahead and, as they say, \"Plug & Play\"! ;)\n\nAD\n\nIn total, I'm at 15 USB devices, that I can think of at once, but 8 are showing up in DCS as configurable, the rest is the likes of headphones, the rift-s, keyboards and mice, and the boom mic.\n\nI think you should be ok, from what I gather the first thing to cause issues is if your devices run low on power something a powered hub should take care of np.\n\nSo far my main devices is the: Crosswinds, the t50 throttle, t50 gimbal, and warbrd lefty stick, and two sets of cougar MFD's.\n\nGranted I don't use the lefty stick in DCS, and might honestly consider not bringing it over to my \"three years and counting\" pit build.\n\nEdited January 27, 2020 by Bob_Bushman"
